ce:section.ce:para:
[Fe(CN)6]3-/4- has excellent electrochemical activity, therefore, it is often used to characterize the electrodes’ electrochemical properties (Fan et al., 2018; Zhao et al., 2019). The performance of electrodes is characterized by cyclic voltammograms (CVs) in 1.0 mM [Fe(CN)6]3-/4-. As shown in Fig. 2
                        , there is a pair of obvious redox peaks of [Fe(CN)6]3-/4- on the bare GCE. On the CDs/GCE, the oxidation peak current (Ipa
                        ) and reduction peak current (Ipc
                        ) are 1.86 times and 1.95 times that of the GCE, respectively, indicating that the CDs have good conductivity and can promote the electrochemical redox reaction of [Fe(CN)6]3-/4-. When the GCE surface is modified with CDs/α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4 nanocomposite, the electrochemical properties are gradually enhanced. The Ipa
                         and Ipc
                         are 2.05 times and 1.91 times that of the CDs/GCE, respectively. It is shown that α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4 nanomaterials can further promote the electrical conductivity of the system, and it can also be explained that the electrochemical properties of CDs/α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4/GCE are better than those of GCE and CDs/GCE. However, When S1 is fixed on the CDs/α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4/GCE, the redox peaks of the system are weakened. The main reason may be that after the modification of S1, the amino group on S1 is bonded to the carboxyl group of CDs/α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4, the negative charge density of the electrode surface is reduced. However, the reaction efficiency of [Fe(CN)6]3-/4- on the CDs/α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4/GCE is hindered by the increasing number of S1 chains adsorbed on the surface of CDs/α-Fe2O3-Fe3O4/GCE.
